-- Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Cadbury Nigeria, KenolKobil, Savannah Move
-- Vincent Nwanma
-- 2010-07-05T18:02:12Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-05/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-cadbury-nigeria-kenolkobil-savannah-move.html

          
          
             Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  increased
for a second day, rising 0.4 percent to 1,660.5 at the close in
Port Louis.  
 Kenya’s  All-Share Index  declined 0.2 percent to 74.03 at
the close in Nairobi. The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share
Index  retreated 0.3 percent to 25,149.59 at the close in Lagos,
spokesman  Sola Oni  said by phone today. Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia
Overall Index  dropped 1.2 percent to 720.04, while the  Ghana
Stock Exchange All-Share Index  fell for a sixth day, decreasing
0.3 percent to 6,524.43.  
 The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  
 Cadbury Nigeria Plc  (CADBURY NL), which makes and markets
confectionery, fell to the lowest in more than a week, dropping
78 kobo, or 2.8 percent, to 26.76 naira. ThisDay reported it
closed a cocoa-processing unit in western Nigeria, Stanmark
Cocoa Processing Co., to prevent dismissed workers from further
disrupting operations.  
 KenolKobil Ltd.  (KNOC KN), a Kenyan fuel retailer with
operations in seven African countries, advanced to the highest
in more than two weeks, rallying 5 cents, or 0.5 percent to 9.9
shillings. Oil climbed for the first day in six, advancing as
much as 0.8 percent to $72.70.  
 Savannah Sugar Estates Co.  (SAVA MP), a Mauritian producer
of the sweetener, rose to the highest since at least July 1995,
climbing 5 Mauritian rupees, or 1 percent to 520 rupees. Sugar
gained to a two-week high on the Liffe exchange in London,
advancing as much as 2.7 percent to $505 a metric ton, on
speculation crop damage will reduce supplies.  
